1
00:00:00,830 --> 00:00:02,700
INSTRUCTOR: Hi,
Data 2100 students.

2
00:00:02,700 --> 00:00:05,180
This lecture is one
of those lectures

3
00:00:05,180 --> 00:00:09,390
that is necessary in the
world of information systems.

4
00:00:09,390 --> 00:00:13,370
It's actually a topic
that many of you

5
00:00:13,370 --> 00:00:16,079
can get a full degree
in project management.

6
00:00:16,079 --> 00:00:21,720
Project management is a
philosophy, a principle content.

7
00:00:21,720 --> 00:00:25,830
It's a practice, if you will,
that is heavily studied.

8
00:00:25,830 --> 00:00:29,310
And as you get into your
perspective industry,

9
00:00:29,310 --> 00:00:30,950
your career, you're
going to notice

10
00:00:30,950 --> 00:00:33,350
that project management looks
different across the board

11
00:00:33,350 --> 00:00:34,800
and from team to team.

12
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,640
So I just want to give you
some foundations of why

13
00:00:37,640 --> 00:00:40,250
project management
matters, some ideas

14
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:43,610
based upon our reading of
why there's different project

15
00:00:43,610 --> 00:00:46,670
management methodologies,
what they're both used for,

16
00:00:46,670 --> 00:00:48,560
and especially in
the world of IT,

17
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:51,020
the systems
development life cycle.

18
00:00:51,020 --> 00:00:54,830
So this is a very
high-level, brief video

19
00:00:54,830 --> 00:00:56,280
about project management.

20
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:58,490
But there's seriously
degrees of--

21
00:00:58,490 --> 00:01:02,160
I mean, so many jobs are
just project managers.

22
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:05,160
There's an element of project
management in every capacity

23
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:07,140
of every job that you work in.

24
00:01:07,140 --> 00:01:09,960
Right now I'm working on
an analytic solution center

25
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:14,880
project, that I'm helping manage
the project that I'm working

26
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:16,690
on requirements gathering.

27
00:01:16,690 --> 00:01:18,600
Those who are working
on the project

28
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:22,650
are working with me to
understand what the end user

29
00:01:22,650 --> 00:01:24,310
would like from the project.

30
00:01:24,310 --> 00:01:26,710
We're doing this
in an agile way.

31
00:01:26,710 --> 00:01:29,580
So we're using all of
these tools and techniques

32
00:01:29,580 --> 00:01:32,940
that you learn in this
class in a project

33
00:01:32,940 --> 00:01:35,050
that students are
working on here at USU

34
00:01:35,050 --> 00:01:39,760
So this is used in all sorts
of different capacities.

35
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:41,680
But why does project
management matter?

36
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:45,430
So project management
defines a plan and schedule.

37
00:01:45,430 --> 00:01:48,270
So project management helps
in defining a clear plan

38
00:01:48,270 --> 00:01:50,200
and schedule for the project.

39
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,700
We ensure that goals are met.

40
00:01:51,700 --> 00:01:55,830
We optimize resource
allocation, so what resources

41
00:01:55,830 --> 00:02:00,480
go where as far as budget,
time, human capacity.

42
00:02:00,480 --> 00:02:02,920
We also improve
team collaboration.

43
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:06,360
So oftentimes, project
management looks like--

44
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:09,449
that you have clearly defined
roles and responsibility

45
00:02:09,449 --> 00:02:12,720
of each person on the team,
and that we're working

46
00:02:12,720 --> 00:02:14,230
towards that common goal.

47
00:02:14,230 --> 00:02:16,810
We also can manage
risk and uncertainties.

48
00:02:16,810 --> 00:02:19,600
There's always risk and
uncertainties with a project--

49
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:21,360
something can go wrong.

50
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:23,280
This proactive
approach helps minimize

51
00:02:23,280 --> 00:02:26,680
the impacts of risks on
the outcome timelines,

52
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:27,850
and what have you.

53
00:02:27,850 --> 00:02:30,820
It also enhances
customer satisfaction.

54
00:02:30,820 --> 00:02:33,090
So us delivering
a project on time

55
00:02:33,090 --> 00:02:36,550
and within budget enhances
customer satisfaction.

56
00:02:36,550 --> 00:02:39,520
So we have the systems
development life cycle.

57
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:42,090
There are seven steps within
that systems development life

58
00:02:42,090 --> 00:02:42,820
cycle.

59
00:02:42,820 --> 00:02:45,940
First off, we start by
planning the project.

60
00:02:45,940 --> 00:02:48,490
So we lay out what does
this project look like,

61
00:02:48,490 --> 00:02:50,590
who's involved, what
are the requirements.

62
00:02:50,590 --> 00:02:52,330
We then analyze the project.

63
00:02:52,330 --> 00:02:54,125
We design the project.

64
00:02:54,125 --> 00:02:57,300
So maybe this looks like
you're developing a website,

65
00:02:57,300 --> 00:03:01,110
and you're going to be
developing a wireframe.

66
00:03:01,110 --> 00:03:03,000
A wireframe of a
website is basically

67
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,910
the bare bones of a website
that shows you, here's what

68
00:03:05,910 --> 00:03:07,990
the first page will look like.

69
00:03:07,990 --> 00:03:10,810
And there's a diagram
that maybe is interactive.

70
00:03:10,810 --> 00:03:12,530
Then we develop that website.

71
00:03:12,530 --> 00:03:15,410
So based upon feedback
that we've been receiving,

72
00:03:15,410 --> 00:03:16,910
we can push to development.

73
00:03:16,910 --> 00:03:17,780
Then we test it.

74
00:03:17,780 --> 00:03:19,610
Does the website work
like we want it to?

75
00:03:19,610 --> 00:03:22,640
We can then implement the
website and then maintain it.

76
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:25,910
So this is not necessarily
just specific to IT,

77
00:03:25,910 --> 00:03:28,280
but it does use technical terms.

78
00:03:28,280 --> 00:03:31,780
But in general, this is what
a life cycle of a project

79
00:03:31,780 --> 00:03:33,150
looks like.

80
00:03:33,150 --> 00:03:35,860
So there's three main
developments within the systems

81
00:03:35,860 --> 00:03:37,160
development life cycle.

82
00:03:37,160 --> 00:03:40,160
The development phase is in
the development environment.

83
00:03:40,160 --> 00:03:41,590
So make sure you know that.

84
00:03:41,590 --> 00:03:44,440
The quality assurance--
so quality assurance

85
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:46,100
is what QA stands for.

86
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:47,270
That's where we test.

87
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:49,900
Does this work like we
think it should be working?

88
00:03:49,900 --> 00:03:51,560
Like it should be working right.

89
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:53,150
And then we finally
implement this.

90
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:55,210
We put it into
production, meaning people

91
00:03:55,210 --> 00:03:56,960
can utilize this website.

92
00:03:56,960 --> 00:03:58,910
They can purchase
things on this website.

93
00:03:58,910 --> 00:04:03,170
This is pushed out into the
greater public, if you will,

94
00:04:03,170 --> 00:04:06,070
to be able to be used, or
if it's an internal project

95
00:04:06,070 --> 00:04:08,230
that those end users
then can finally

96
00:04:08,230 --> 00:04:10,520
use whatever you just produced.

97
00:04:10,520 --> 00:04:13,700
We also have two ideas
of project management.

98
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:16,970
So we have the agile approach
and the waterfall approach.

99
00:04:16,970 --> 00:04:20,740
The agile methodology is
really helpful for when

100
00:04:20,740 --> 00:04:23,360
you're starting a project.

101
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:24,910
The client really
isn't sure what

102
00:04:24,910 --> 00:04:26,870
they want at the
beginning of the project.

103
00:04:26,870 --> 00:04:28,090
Sometimes this looks like--

104
00:04:28,090 --> 00:04:32,260
I had my own website development
company for some time,

105
00:04:32,260 --> 00:04:34,552
and I would meet with
a client and based

106
00:04:34,552 --> 00:04:36,260
upon what the client
was saying, like oh,

107
00:04:36,260 --> 00:04:38,180
this is going to be
the agile approach.

108
00:04:38,180 --> 00:04:41,050
The requirements of
the project weren't

109
00:04:41,050 --> 00:04:43,760
really well-defined I'd
ask follow-up questions,

110
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:45,730
and it seemed like
there was some area

111
00:04:45,730 --> 00:04:46,970
that they hadn't considered.

112
00:04:46,970 --> 00:04:51,280
So with agile, basically, you
work through this entire systems

113
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:54,562
development life cycle
in a span of a sprint,

114
00:04:54,562 --> 00:04:55,520
is what they're called.

115
00:04:55,520 --> 00:04:57,920
So generally, sprints
are two weeks.

116
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:00,950
So at the first of that
two weeks you're planning,

117
00:05:00,950 --> 00:05:03,380
what does this sprint need
to accomplish by the end?

118
00:05:03,380 --> 00:05:07,880
So if you're working on, say,
a Contact Us page on a website,

119
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:10,280
you plan out that one page.

120
00:05:10,280 --> 00:05:13,300
You analyze the needs,
you design the needs,

121
00:05:13,300 --> 00:05:15,250
you develop that one page.

122
00:05:15,250 --> 00:05:17,540
You test that one page.

123
00:05:17,540 --> 00:05:20,275
You implement that one page.

124
00:05:20,275 --> 00:05:22,560
And at that very end
of those two weeks,

125
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:25,880
you get feedback from your
client who says, oh, I

126
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:29,100
like this part of the page,
change that part of the page.

127
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:32,750
And you have a potentially--
we call it shippable product

128
00:05:32,750 --> 00:05:36,770
by the end of that two weeks.

129
00:05:36,770 --> 00:05:38,480
And then the next
two weeks, say you're

130
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:41,850
going to work on the home
page of the website, right.

131
00:05:41,850 --> 00:05:44,270
So you're breaking
down the project

132
00:05:44,270 --> 00:05:47,030
into its component parts.

133
00:05:47,030 --> 00:05:49,160
And so you're getting
a ton of feedback

134
00:05:49,160 --> 00:05:51,720
with the client on what's
working and what's not.

135
00:05:51,720 --> 00:05:54,650
A waterfall is
more, so you're just

136
00:05:54,650 --> 00:05:57,510
going through each of
these phases one time.

137
00:05:57,510 --> 00:06:02,330
So maybe it's a security
system at a bank.

138
00:06:02,330 --> 00:06:05,310
Say, it's somebody at
America First Bank,

139
00:06:05,310 --> 00:06:07,880
and they're going around to
all the brick-and-mortar banks

140
00:06:07,880 --> 00:06:09,900
to implement this
new security system.

141
00:06:09,900 --> 00:06:12,620
If they've done it so
many times and it's really

142
00:06:12,620 --> 00:06:13,890
well thought out--

143
00:06:13,890 --> 00:06:17,730
it's very much a
lockstep approach--

144
00:06:17,730 --> 00:06:18,890
then a waterfall may work.

145
00:06:18,890 --> 00:06:20,810
And a waterfall looks
like I'm in the planning

146
00:06:20,810 --> 00:06:23,760
phase for some time and the
analysis phase for some time,

147
00:06:23,760 --> 00:06:25,560
in the design phase
for some time,

148
00:06:25,560 --> 00:06:27,540
the development
phase for some time,

149
00:06:27,540 --> 00:06:30,390
the testing phase for some
time, and implementation

150
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:31,720
phase for some time.

151
00:06:31,720 --> 00:06:34,870
We do not circle
back up in waterfall.

152
00:06:34,870 --> 00:06:38,380
Waterfall, you are in planning
phase for a period of time,

153
00:06:38,380 --> 00:06:40,840
then you go into
analysis, then design.

154
00:06:40,840 --> 00:06:42,352
So just keep that in mind.

155
00:06:42,352 --> 00:06:43,810
There's those two
different phases.

156
00:06:43,810 --> 00:06:45,820
Both have their pros and cons.

157
00:06:45,820 --> 00:06:48,270
Generally, you're
going to see a mix.

158
00:06:48,270 --> 00:06:54,030
But most teams are wanting to
be agile in their methodology.

159
00:06:54,030 --> 00:06:58,732
Finally, the element of
scope creep with projects.

160
00:06:58,732 --> 00:07:00,930
Part of this will look
like-- a lot of my examples

161
00:07:00,930 --> 00:07:03,460
are websites or data
analysis projects.

162
00:07:03,460 --> 00:07:05,890
But scope creep you
meet with the client.

163
00:07:05,890 --> 00:07:09,430
They say, I want a website
that is four pages.

164
00:07:09,430 --> 00:07:12,940
And so you work with them
over a series of sprints.

165
00:07:12,940 --> 00:07:15,870
You meet with them
and then you can

166
00:07:15,870 --> 00:07:18,570
start to see that they're
like, oh, actually,

167
00:07:18,570 --> 00:07:20,470
we might want to
add another page,

168
00:07:20,470 --> 00:07:23,460
or we might want to add another
capability on an existing page

169
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:25,180
that we didn't know about.

170
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:28,200
So that just means that the
project is growing and growing

171
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:33,060
and growing, which, if you can
communicate with the client,

172
00:07:33,060 --> 00:07:34,360
is going to cost more money.

173
00:07:34,360 --> 00:07:36,670
It's going to take
more resources.

174
00:07:36,670 --> 00:07:38,140
It's going to take more time.

175
00:07:38,140 --> 00:07:40,360
Then you can come to
some sort of agreement.

176
00:07:40,360 --> 00:07:44,110
But scope creep oftentimes
is the fail of most projects

177
00:07:44,110 --> 00:07:47,550
because you let it get so big
that you don't condense it down

178
00:07:47,550 --> 00:07:49,900
into, OK, what is the
most important parts?

179
00:07:49,900 --> 00:07:53,490
And be firm when you're
working in a project

180
00:07:53,490 --> 00:07:56,820
and considering what is
originally part of this project

181
00:07:56,820 --> 00:08:00,750
and what is being added to it
that we need to either save

182
00:08:00,750 --> 00:08:04,150
for another project or up
the budget, up the timeline,

183
00:08:04,150 --> 00:08:05,680
those types of things.

184
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,720
So that's a little bit
about project management.

185
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:10,150
Again, there is degrees in this.

186
00:08:10,150 --> 00:08:11,860
There's whole careers
devoted to this,

187
00:08:11,860 --> 00:08:13,650
but I just want you
to think about how

188
00:08:13,650 --> 00:08:15,160
we manage big projects.

189
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:18,270
And you have projects going
on at either at your work

190
00:08:18,270 --> 00:08:21,310
or in school that there is an
element of project management

191
00:08:21,310 --> 00:08:23,940
that communication and making
sure those deliverables are

192
00:08:23,940 --> 00:08:25,180
met on time.

193
00:08:25,180 --> 00:08:27,180
But something to keep
in mind here as we're

194
00:08:27,180 --> 00:08:29,020
setting information in business.

195
00:08:29,020 --> 00:08:31,500
Take care, everybody.